A six-digit number (base 10) is considered squarish if it satisfies the following conditions: 
(i) none of its digits are zero; 
(ii) it is a perfect square divisible by 16; 
(iii) the first two digits, the middle two digits, and the last two digits of the number are all perfect squares when considered as two-digit numbers. 
How many such squarish numbers exist?
$\text{(A)} \ 0 \qquad  \text{(B)} \ 2 \qquad  \text{(C)} \ 3 \qquad  \text{(D)} \ 4 \qquad  \text{(E)} \ 5$
